<% content_for :title, "Hybrid EdDSA + ML-DSA" %>

<section class="space-y-8">
  <header class="space-y-2">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Hybrid EdDSA + ML-DSA</h1>
    <p class="text-slate-700">
      Sign with both Ed25519 and ML-DSA so a break in either algorithm alone
      still leaves the token authenticated.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="space-y-3">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">Why hybrid</h2>
    <p>
      ML-DSA is young. It is a NIST standard, it has been thoroughly analysed,
      and it is the right long-term bet — but it has not yet absorbed the
      decades of cryptanalysis that RSA and elliptic curves have. Likewise,
      Ed25519 is rock-solid against classical adversaries but falls to a
      cryptographically-relevant quantum computer. A signature that requires
      <em>both</em> a valid Ed25519 signature and a valid ML-DSA signature is
      only forgeable by an attacker who can break both algorithms.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hybrid mode is transitional. Run it while the industry gains
      confidence in ML-DSA alone. Dropping to pure ML-DSA later is a
      single-field change in the JWT header.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-3">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">Usage</h2>
    <pre class="bg-slate-50 p-4 rounded text-sm overflow-auto"><code class="language-ruby">require "jwt/pq"

key   = JWT::PQ::HybridKey.generate(:ml_dsa_65)
token = JWT.encode({ sub: "u-1" }, key, "EdDSA+ML-DSA-65")

payload, header = JWT.decode(
  token, key, true, algorithms: ["EdDSA+ML-DSA-65"]
)
header["alg"]  # =&gt; "EdDSA+ML-DSA-65"</code></pre>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-3">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">Wire format</h2>
    <p>
      A hybrid JWT's signature section is the concatenation of the Ed25519
      signature (64 bytes) followed by the ML-DSA signature for the chosen
      parameter set. Both cover the same signing input
      (<code>base64url(header) + "." + base64url(payload)</code>), and
      both must verify. An attacker must forge both to pass verification.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-3">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">Cost</h2>
    <p>
      Token size is dominated by the ML-DSA portion. An
      <code>EdDSA+ML-DSA-65</code> signature is ~3357 B — the ML-DSA signature
      plus 64 bytes. CPU cost is dominated by ML-DSA too; Ed25519 verification
      is fractions of the ML-DSA cost.
    </p>
  </section>
</section>
